Theory:

PHP:
PHP stands for "PHP: Hypertext Preprocessor". It is a widely-used, open source server-side scripting language. PHP scripts are executed on the server and it is free to download and use.

Why PHP?
- PHP runs on all major platforms (Windows, Linux, Unix, Mac OS X, etc.)
- PHP is compatible with all leading web servers (Nginx, Apache, Microsoft IIS, etc.)
- PHP supports a wide range of databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, MS SQL, Oracle, MongoDB, etc.)
- PHP is free. Download it from www.php.net
- PHP is easy to learn and runs efficiently on the server side

What is XAMPP?
XAMPP stands for Cross-Platform (X), Apache (A), MariaDB (M), PHP (P), and Perl (P). It allows developers to test and debug their websites or applications in a local environment before deploying them. It is one of the most popular and user-friendly local server solutions.

- Cross-Platform (X): Runs on Windows, Linux, and macOS.
- Apache (A): Web server that handles requests and delivers web content.
- MariaDB (M): A fork of MySQL, used for managing the database of web applications.
- PHP (P): Server-side scripting language used to create dynamic web content.
- Perl (P): High-level scripting language for text processing and automation.

Connecting PHP to MySQL:
To connect PHP to MySQL, use the MySQLi (MySQL Improved) or PDO (PHP Data Objects) extension. Both support prepared statements which are important for security against SQL injection attacks.

